 1 
00:00:13,401 --> 00:00:15,336
[Helicopter Approaching]

 2 
00:00:43,947 --> 00:00:45,779
Red Baron, control,
Red Baron 5.

 3 
00:00:45,850 --> 00:00:48,285
Radio:
Go ahead, Red Baron 5.

 4 
00:00:48,354 --> 00:00:51,450
Roger. Orbiting southeast
corner sector Alpha Charlie.

 5 
00:00:51,525 --> 00:00:53,756
We've spotted what
appears to be a spacecraft

 6 
00:00:53,829 --> 00:00:55,627
just outside the surfline.

 7 
00:00:55,698 --> 00:00:59,466
Alert Rescue and advise
to remain on station for 45 minutes.

 8 
00:00:59,537 --> 00:01:02,029
And we'll squat 7700
for a radar fix.

 9 
00:01:02,108 --> 00:01:04,373
Radio:
Roger.

 10 
00:01:04,444 --> 00:01:06,003
Rescue,
I have Red Baron 5.

 11 
00:01:06,080 --> 00:01:08,573
Report a possible
spacecraft offshore

 12 
00:01:08,652 --> 00:01:10,644
southeast sector
Alpha Charlie.

 13 
00:01:10,721 --> 00:01:13,486
Immediately launch chopper.
Effect pickup and recovery .

 14 
00:01:13,558 --> 00:01:14,856
Base radar will vector.

 15 
00:02:11,246 --> 00:02:12,874
Man:
Every body out! Come on!

 16 
00:02:12,949 --> 00:02:16,182
Let's go!
Ha! Ha! Ha!

 17 
00:02:20,594 --> 00:02:22,529
Sergeant, get that
half-track down here

 18 
00:02:22,597 --> 00:02:24,589
and get a cable out
to those frogmen.

 19 
00:02:24,666 --> 00:02:26,635
Yes, sir!

 20 
00:03:08,466 --> 00:03:10,401
The general, sir.

 21 
00:03:16,145 --> 00:03:18,080
Anybody in that thing?

 22 
00:03:18,148 --> 00:03:20,583
I don't know, sir.
We just beached it.

 23 
00:03:28,096 --> 00:03:30,031
All right,
open her up.

 24 
00:03:30,099 --> 00:03:31,829
Open it up!

 25 
00:04:11,495 --> 00:04:13,691
Welcome, gentlemen,
to the United Sta--

 26 
00:06:40,255 --> 00:06:42,589
- Did you call the zoo?
- Yes, sir, we're in luck.

 27 
00:06:42,659 --> 00:06:45,356
Sick bay's almost empty,
except for a mauled fox cub

 28 
00:06:45,429 --> 00:06:48,161
and a deer with pneumonia
and a depressed gorilla.

 29 
00:06:48,234 --> 00:06:51,466
The apes will be hidden from the public.
They'll be quarantined.

 30 
00:06:51,538 --> 00:06:54,407
They need medical attention,
it's available right on the spot.

 31 
00:06:54,477 --> 00:06:57,276
And the experts can start giving them
the once-over first thing tomorrow.

 32 
00:06:57,347 --> 00:06:59,874
- General Brody's very pleased.
- Oh, me too, me too.

 33 
00:06:59,952 --> 00:07:03,286
We can't allow monkeys to leave
their messes on the floor, huh?

 34 
00:07:03,356 --> 00:07:05,291
Have they been fed?
Raw steak or something?

 35 
00:07:05,359 --> 00:07:07,727
The zoo tells me that chimpanzees,
like all apes,

 36 
00:07:07,797 --> 00:07:09,766
are vegetarians, sir.

 37 
00:07:09,833 --> 00:07:12,701
They suggested oranges.

 38 
00:07:12,771 --> 00:07:14,569
Good God!

 39 
00:07:20,582 --> 00:07:22,517
What's the matter, Corporal?

 40 
00:07:26,763 --> 00:07:29,665
Excuse me. I didn't mean to
disturb you while you're dressing.

 41 
00:07:31,403 --> 00:07:33,429
What the hell am I saying?

 42 
00:07:33,506 --> 00:07:35,441
They're pretending to dress, sir.

 43 
00:07:35,509 --> 00:07:37,444
What do you mean pretending?
They are dressing up!

 44 
00:07:37,512 --> 00:07:39,947
- Where did they get clothes?
- They brought them with them, sir.

 45 
00:07:40,015 --> 00:07:42,884
- What?
- In that suitcase.

 46 
00:07:42,954 --> 00:07:44,980
Suitcase?

 47 
00:07:50,499 --> 00:07:52,468
Uh...

 48 
00:07:52,535 --> 00:07:55,734
Greg, maybe you should
give them their oranges.

 49 
00:08:40,508 --> 00:08:42,943
Uh, well, they're--

 50 
00:08:43,011 --> 00:08:45,139
They're going
to the zoo infirmary .

 51 
00:08:45,215 --> 00:08:48,778
Arrange for a police escort
at 1 630 hours.

 52 
00:08:48,854 --> 00:08:51,187
They'll have company there.

 53 
00:08:51,257 --> 00:08:53,317
There's a gorilla
in the next cage.

 54 
00:08:55,163 --> 00:08:57,064
Why did he do that?

 55 
00:09:03,576 --> 00:09:05,511
[Animals Screeching]

 56 
00:09:33,154 --> 00:09:35,316
Here you are, old fella.

 57 
00:09:41,333 --> 00:09:43,768
Boy, you really are sick.

 58 
00:10:00,862 --> 00:10:04,800
Hello, missy.
Have a banana.

 59 
00:10:04,868 --> 00:10:07,100
Have it your own way, mate.

 60 
00:10:21,728 --> 00:10:26,600
- Zira!
- I'm not his mate. I'm yours.

 61 
00:10:26,669 --> 00:10:30,573
Control yourself.
I think they're trying to be kind.

 62 
00:10:30,642 --> 00:10:34,080
This cage stinks of gorilla.

 63 
00:10:37,919 --> 00:10:42,085
Cornelius, where are we?
What's happened?

 64 
00:10:42,159 --> 00:10:45,756
I know where we are.
I know what has happened.

 65 
00:10:45,831 --> 00:10:49,097
In some fashion--

 66 
00:10:49,169 --> 00:10:52,766
and I lack the intellect
to know precisely how--

 67 
00:10:52,841 --> 00:10:55,971
we have traveled from Earth's future
to Earth's past.

 68 
00:10:56,047 --> 00:10:58,608
But we saw
the Earth destroyed.

 69 
00:10:58,684 --> 00:11:02,281
And Earth will be destroyed
just as we saw it.

 70 
00:11:02,356 --> 00:11:04,689
Only since seeing it,
we have passed through

 71 
00:11:04,759 --> 00:11:06,956
a backward disturbance in time.

 72 
00:11:07,030 --> 00:11:11,526
Did you notice the date meter clicking
down after the shock wave hit our ship?

 73 
00:11:11,603 --> 00:11:14,129
Yes.

 74 
00:11:14,207 --> 00:11:17,337
We have returned to Earth nearly
2,000 years before its destruction.

 75 
00:11:17,412 --> 00:11:20,850
That is another reason
for us to keep silent.

 76 
00:11:20,918 --> 00:11:23,251
Our human captors will not
be edified to learn

 77 
00:11:23,321 --> 00:11:25,813
that one day their world
will crack like an egg

 78 
00:11:25,891 --> 00:11:28,828
and burn to a cinder because
ofan ape war ofaggression.

 79 
00:11:28,896 --> 00:11:31,730
[Growling]

 80 
00:11:36,174 --> 00:11:39,976
Apes, at this instant in time,

 81 
00:11:40,047 --> 00:11:42,312
cannot yet talk.

 82 
00:11:42,383 --> 00:11:45,980
For the moment,
we should follow their example.

 83 
00:11:48,693 --> 00:11:51,255
[Tiger Roars]

 84 
00:11:51,331 --> 00:11:54,597
[Elephant Trumpets]

 85 
00:11:55,670 --> 00:11:57,536
[Bear Roars]

 86 
00:11:57,607 --> 00:12:00,099
Oh, the driver gave me
this report from the air base.

 87 
00:12:00,177 --> 00:12:02,510
Better read it
before we start the test.

 88 
00:12:03,883 --> 00:12:06,011
Yeah, it's the usual
imitative behavior.

 89 
00:12:06,086 --> 00:12:08,886
"Mimicking salutes,
handshaking, sitting on chairs,

 90 
00:12:08,957 --> 00:12:12,554
eating offplates with knives."

 91 
00:12:12,630 --> 00:12:15,759
- Well, what is it, Lewis?
- There was sort of
a carpetbag on the ship.

 92 
00:12:15,834 --> 00:12:21,537
- Full offood?
- No, clothes and it seems
they changed into them.

 93 
00:12:21,609 --> 00:12:23,578
I don't believe it.

 94 
00:12:31,892 --> 00:12:33,724
[Bear Roars]

 95 
00:12:57,598 --> 00:13:00,193
Hi, Dr. Dixon.
Dr. Branton.

 96 
00:13:00,268 --> 00:13:02,169
- Good morning, Arthur.
- Morning.

 97 
00:13:15,491 --> 00:13:18,951
- The female's a bit uppity, sir.
- Oh? Okay, I'll be careful.

 98 
00:13:19,030 --> 00:13:21,226
I see you've prepared
the Wisconsin multiphasic.

 99 
00:13:21,300 --> 00:13:23,292
We'll begin with that.

 100 
00:13:27,142 --> 00:13:29,168
Um, go easy now, Stevie.

 101 
00:13:29,245 --> 00:13:31,772
Oh, they look
pretty docile to me.

 102 
00:13:31,850 --> 00:13:34,945
Yes, but don't
take any chances.

 103 
00:13:37,525 --> 00:13:40,051
Unless the spacecraft
was remotely controlled,

 104 
00:13:40,129 --> 00:13:42,621
they must have been conditioned to push
at least some of the right buttons.

 105 
00:13:42,699 --> 00:13:45,397
I mean, they can't be morons.

 106 
00:13:45,470 --> 00:13:47,905
All right,
we'll take the female first.

 107 
00:13:47,974 --> 00:13:50,968
Arthur, would you set up a cha--

 108 
00:14:12,878 --> 00:14:14,904
Well, she seems
to be pretty smart.

 109 
00:14:14,982 --> 00:14:18,613
All right,
let's make it more diffcult.

 110 
00:15:04,189 --> 00:15:07,160
They, uh, haven't had
their breakfast yet?

 111 
00:15:07,227 --> 00:15:09,492
Not a bite.
Just as you ordered.

 112 
00:15:10,900 --> 00:15:13,802
Good. We'll offer the banana.

 113 
00:16:09,312 --> 00:16:11,372
[Sighs]

 114 
00:16:14,220 --> 00:16:18,921
- Well, why doesn't she take it?
- Because I loathe bananas!

 115 
00:16:18,994 --> 00:16:22,830
- Zira!
- I don't believe it.

 116 
00:16:22,899 --> 00:16:27,236
Yes. Arthur, I think
Dr. Branton needs some air.

 117 
00:16:31,646 --> 00:16:33,444
Zira, are you mad?

 118 
00:16:33,516 --> 00:16:35,815
Dr. Milo, please,
do not call my wife mad!

 119 
00:16:35,886 --> 00:16:38,355
I did not call her mad.
I merely asked her ifshe was!

 120 
00:16:38,423 --> 00:16:40,585
And I repeat the question.
Are you mad?

 121 
00:16:40,659 --> 00:16:44,062
- I hate deceit!
- Well, there is a time for truth

 122 
00:16:44,132 --> 00:16:46,363
and a time not for lies,
but for silence.

 123 
00:16:46,435 --> 00:16:48,667
And until we know who our friends are
and who our enemies--

 124 
00:16:48,739 --> 00:16:52,472
And how in the name ofGod are we
to know that unless we communicate?

 125 
00:16:52,545 --> 00:16:55,310
- We can speak, so I spoke.
- And we can listen!

 126 
00:16:55,382 --> 00:16:57,317
Yes, to a lot of
psychiatric small talk!

 127 
00:16:57,385 --> 00:17:00,014
- And we can watch.
- A display ofprimitive apparatus!

 128 
00:17:00,090 --> 00:17:02,218
Primitive?
It's prehistoric!

 129 
00:17:02,293 --> 00:17:05,058
- Couldn't test
the intelligence of a newt!
- Calm yourself, Zira!

 130 
00:17:05,130 --> 00:17:08,067
- I am calm!
- Zira! Zira!

 131 
00:17:08,135 --> 00:17:11,037
- Stop arguing!
- [Grunting]

 132 
00:17:11,106 --> 00:17:13,041
It's too late for that.

 133 
00:17:13,109 --> 00:17:15,271
Use your heads
and start thinking.

 134 
00:17:15,345 --> 00:17:17,838
Now that they know we can speak,
how much will we tell them?

 135 
00:17:19,118 --> 00:17:22,351
- Milo!
- [Gorilla Growling]

 136 
00:17:23,492 --> 00:17:25,961
[Trumpets]

 137 
00:17:26,029 --> 00:17:27,861
[Roars]

 138 
00:17:29,334 --> 00:17:31,599
[Door Slams Shut]

 139 
00:17:46,994 --> 00:17:48,929
We'll need a full autopsy.

 140 
00:17:48,997 --> 00:17:51,159
With special emphasis
on the cranial and oral areas.

 141 
00:17:51,234 --> 00:17:53,863
Let us know when the report comes in.
Will you, please?

 142 
00:17:56,976 --> 00:17:58,968
I'd better do this alone.

 143 
00:18:00,148 --> 00:18:02,208
[Monkey Screeches]

 144 
00:18:15,036 --> 00:18:19,976
Um, we mean you no harm.

 145 
00:18:20,044 --> 00:18:24,073
Do you understand?
We will not hurt you.

 146 
00:18:24,150 --> 00:18:27,451
- Poor Dr. Milo.
- Doctor?

 147 
00:18:27,522 --> 00:18:29,923
Yes. Doctor.
You killed him!

 148 
00:18:29,992 --> 00:18:32,427
No, I didn't. He did.

 149 
00:18:32,496 --> 00:18:35,899
- One of your own kind.
- Zira: He's a gorilla!

 150 
00:18:35,968 --> 00:18:38,437
Well, look, there's
nothing to be afraid of.

 151 
00:18:38,506 --> 00:18:41,999
You see, he's in chains.
He's under sedation.

 152 
00:18:42,077 --> 00:18:44,046
Do you understand that?

 153 
00:18:44,113 --> 00:18:46,879
I should. I've been doing it
halfmy life to humans.

 154 
00:18:46,952 --> 00:18:48,853
Humans?

 155 
00:18:48,921 --> 00:18:51,516
I'm a psychiatrist.

 156 
00:18:51,592 --> 00:18:55,553
Oh, well, I'm--I'm
a psychiatrist too.

 157 
00:18:57,802 --> 00:19:00,795
Do you have a name?

 158 
00:19:05,179 --> 00:19:07,114
My name is Cornelius.

 159 
00:19:07,182 --> 00:19:09,117
This is my wife Zira.

 160 
00:19:09,185 --> 00:19:12,520
And I'm Lewis.
Lewis Dixon.

 161 
00:19:12,590 --> 00:19:15,561
Nobody's going to believe this.

 162 
00:19:15,629 --> 00:19:16,960
Believe what?

 163 
00:19:17,030 --> 00:19:19,830
- That primitive apes can talk.
- Primitive?

 164 
00:19:19,901 --> 00:19:24,397
Uh...well, I mean
that in our, um...

 165 
00:19:24,475 --> 00:19:28,607
primitive, um, civilization,
apes just don't talk.

 166 
00:19:28,682 --> 00:19:30,617
I mean, I think
it's important that when

 167 
00:19:30,685 --> 00:19:34,087
our primitive security
precautions are lifted,

 168 
00:19:34,156 --> 00:19:37,150
that the first time
you say anything in public,

 169 
00:19:37,228 --> 00:19:39,993
you should talk
to what we primitively call

 170 
00:19:40,065 --> 00:19:42,331
the right people.

 171 
00:19:45,273 --> 00:19:47,606
May I say something...

 172 
00:19:47,677 --> 00:19:49,612
personal?

 173 
00:19:49,680 --> 00:19:51,615
Please.

 174 
00:19:51,683 --> 00:19:53,584
I like you.

 175 
00:19:57,959 --> 00:20:00,292
I have from the beginning.

 176 
00:20:10,445 --> 00:20:12,311
[Murmuring]

 177 
00:20:15,252 --> 00:20:17,778
- Good afternoon, gentlemen.
- All: Mr. President.

 178 
00:20:17,856 --> 00:20:21,692
I'm aware that what I have to
tell you may conceivably create
a credibility gap

 179 
00:20:21,762 --> 00:20:24,323
- somewhat wider than the Grand Canyon.
- [Laughing]

 180 
00:20:24,399 --> 00:20:28,132
Nonetheless, it is true.
Yesterday, a U.S. spacecraft

 181 
00:20:28,205 --> 00:20:31,438
splashed down off
the Southern California coast.

 182 
00:20:31,510 --> 00:20:33,479
It was one of two that
have been missing in space

 183 
00:20:33,546 --> 00:20:35,515
for over 2 years now.

 184 
00:20:35,583 --> 00:20:38,577
To be exact, the one commanded
by Colonel Taylor.

 185 
00:20:38,654 --> 00:20:40,213
[Murmuring]

 186 
00:20:40,290 --> 00:20:42,521
Have they identified the bodies,
Mr. President?

 187 
00:20:42,594 --> 00:20:47,590
They have identified
3 bodies, yes, all living.

 188 
00:20:47,667 --> 00:20:49,499
[Murmuring]

 189 
00:20:49,570 --> 00:20:53,167
At the time of their rescue,
through an unfortunate accident

 190 
00:20:53,243 --> 00:20:56,305
one of them was killed early
this morning in the Los Angeles Zoo.

 191 
00:20:56,381 --> 00:20:58,748
- Zoo?
- What would astronauts

 192 
00:20:58,818 --> 00:21:01,049
be doing in a zoo,
Mr. President?

 193 
00:21:01,121 --> 00:21:05,025
They are not astronauts,
General Faulkner.

 194 
00:21:05,094 --> 00:21:07,564
- They are apes.
- [Murmuring]

 195 
00:21:07,632 --> 00:21:09,567
Chimpanzees,
to be more precise.

 196 
00:21:09,635 --> 00:21:12,332
They're harmless, friendly,
and by all reports

 197 
00:21:12,405 --> 00:21:14,967
extremely intelligent
and sophisticated creatures.

 198 
00:21:15,043 --> 00:21:16,978
But naturally, being animals,

 199 
00:21:17,046 --> 00:21:20,244
they cannot tell us
where the ship came from

 200 
00:21:20,317 --> 00:21:22,651
or how they
came to be in it.

 201 
00:21:22,721 --> 00:21:24,815
I have, therefore,
decided to convene

 202 
00:21:24,891 --> 00:21:28,328
a Presidential Commission of lnquiry
in Los Angeles tomorrow.

 203 
00:21:28,397 --> 00:21:30,958
The 2 surviving apes

 204 
00:21:31,034 --> 00:21:34,004
will be presented to the commission
for their inspection.

 205 
00:21:34,071 --> 00:21:37,474
The press will be invited to attend,
not to participate.

 206 
00:21:37,543 --> 00:21:40,673
I don't believe
that we can withhold

 207 
00:21:40,748 --> 00:21:45,687
this extraordinary discovery
from the world any longer.

 208 
00:21:45,756 --> 00:21:47,691
[Speaking French]

 209 
00:21:52,233 --> 00:21:54,168
[Speaking German]

 210 
00:21:58,041 --> 00:21:59,976
[SpeakingJapanese]

 211 
00:22:04,117 --> 00:22:06,052
One of the 2
American spaceships

 212 
00:22:06,120 --> 00:22:08,612
believed until now to have
disintegrated in orbit,

 213 
00:22:08,690 --> 00:22:12,025
splashed down unexpectedly yesterday
in the Pacific Ocean

 214 
00:22:12,096 --> 00:22:14,122
off the coast
ofSouthern California.

 215 
00:22:14,199 --> 00:22:17,295
And is stated
to have been manned--

 216 
00:22:17,371 --> 00:22:21,241
if you can call it manned--
by monkeys.

 217 
00:22:21,310 --> 00:22:23,677
Reporters:
General!

 218 
00:22:23,747 --> 00:22:26,216
No comment.
I have nothing to say, gentlemen.

 219 
00:22:26,285 --> 00:22:28,379
- Reporters: Senator!
- I'm sorry , boys, not now.

 220 
00:22:28,454 --> 00:22:30,548
I haven't the time now.
A little later, please.

 221 
00:22:30,624 --> 00:22:32,593
Reporter:
Here comes the chairman.

 222 
00:22:32,661 --> 00:22:34,596
Later. Later.

 223 
00:22:38,670 --> 00:22:41,003
As the president's
senior science advisor,

 224 
00:22:41,073 --> 00:22:44,875
what do you expect to experience
from this historic meeting?

 225 
00:22:44,946 --> 00:22:47,940
- Fear.
- [All Talking At Once]

 226 
00:22:53,258 --> 00:22:55,660
All right now,
after I break the news,

 227 
00:22:55,729 --> 00:22:58,528
I want you to start slowly
with simple answers to what will

 228 
00:22:58,600 --> 00:23:00,796
certainly be
simple questions.

 229 
00:23:00,869 --> 00:23:03,635
And if the questions
become less simple?

 230 
00:23:03,708 --> 00:23:07,840
- Be yourself.
- Your better self, Zira.

 231 
00:23:07,914 --> 00:23:10,976
- Please.
- [Knock]
Man: They're ready, sir.

 232 
00:23:11,052 --> 00:23:12,987
All right, it's time.

 233 
00:23:14,791 --> 00:23:17,693
What do they think
we are, gorillas?

 234 
00:23:17,762 --> 00:23:19,890
I'm sorry .

 235 
00:23:33,156 --> 00:23:35,216
That's it.
Just be seated.

 236 
00:23:36,394 --> 00:23:39,923
Uh, Mr. Chairman,
members of the commission,

 237 
00:23:40,000 --> 00:23:43,164
Iadies and gentlemen,
my name is Lewis Dixon.

 238 
00:23:43,238 --> 00:23:45,435
And I am
the animal psychiatrist

 239 
00:23:45,508 --> 00:23:47,977
who has been in charge
of these 2 apes

 240 
00:23:48,045 --> 00:23:50,344
since they came to
the Los Angeles Zoo.

 241 
00:23:50,415 --> 00:23:53,250
My associate,
Dr. Stephanie Branton

 242 
00:23:53,320 --> 00:23:55,516
and I are ready
to answer your questions.

 243 
00:23:55,590 --> 00:23:59,050
What may astonish you
is that, um,

 244 
00:23:59,129 --> 00:24:01,121
our chimpanzee friends

 245 
00:24:01,199 --> 00:24:04,465
are ready to answer
your questions too.

 246 
00:24:04,536 --> 00:24:07,234
Not by signs, not by looks,
or movements,

 247 
00:24:07,308 --> 00:24:09,869
but by words.

 248 
00:24:09,945 --> 00:24:11,880
- Ha ha ha!
- Ha ha ha!

 249 
00:24:13,117 --> 00:24:15,882
[Gavel Strikes Bench]

 250 
00:24:15,954 --> 00:24:19,221
Dr. Dixon, as a zoologist,
I know and respect your work,

 251 
00:24:19,293 --> 00:24:21,888
but if you think you're going to turn
a presidential inquiry

 252 
00:24:21,963 --> 00:24:24,490
into a ventriloquist's act,
I have to inform you--

 253 
00:24:24,567 --> 00:24:26,502
And I have to inform you, sir,
that these two apes

 254 
00:24:26,570 --> 00:24:28,505
have acquired
the power ofspeech.

 255 
00:24:28,573 --> 00:24:30,804
Come now, Doctor,
you know as well as I do

 256 
00:24:30,877 --> 00:24:32,812
their brain system
is not developed

 257 
00:24:32,880 --> 00:24:35,680
in either the vocal or
abstract thinking area.

 258 
00:24:35,751 --> 00:24:38,118
Yes, sir, but I repeat
that they have the power ofspeech.

 259 
00:24:38,188 --> 00:24:41,751
And it is for you gentlemen
to assess how far that power

 260 
00:24:41,827 --> 00:24:43,762
can be exercised intelligently.

 261 
00:24:43,830 --> 00:24:47,666
Well, may we be told which
is the female of the species?

 262 
00:24:51,909 --> 00:24:55,074
Did she rise as a reflex
to you having indicated her,

 263 
00:24:55,147 --> 00:24:57,116
or in answer to my question?

 264 
00:24:57,184 --> 00:24:59,676
That's for you to decide.

 265 
00:25:01,590 --> 00:25:04,823
- Have you a name?
- Zira.

 266 
00:25:04,895 --> 00:25:06,830
[Crowd Gasps]

 267 
00:25:06,898 --> 00:25:08,833
Certainly she can articulate,

 268 
00:25:08,901 --> 00:25:11,530
which, in itself,
is extraordinary !

 269 
00:25:11,605 --> 00:25:15,134
Uh, but, Dr. Dixon, are we
to infer that Zira is her name

 270 
00:25:15,211 --> 00:25:17,476
or some phrase
in her language?

 271 
00:25:17,547 --> 00:25:19,482
Infer what you will,
Mr. Chairman.

 272 
00:25:19,550 --> 00:25:21,815
I suggest you
rephrase the question.

 273 
00:25:25,459 --> 00:25:27,360
What is your name?

 274 
00:25:27,429 --> 00:25:29,398
Zi-ra!

 275 
00:25:31,335 --> 00:25:33,737
One might as well
be talking to a parrot.

 276 
00:25:33,806 --> 00:25:36,071
A parrot!

 277 
00:25:38,813 --> 00:25:42,774
Mechanical mimicry . Unique in
an ape vocally, without a doubt,

 278 
00:25:42,852 --> 00:25:45,914
but, uh, does
the other one talk?

 279 
00:25:48,327 --> 00:25:51,025
Only when she lets me.

 280 
00:25:51,099 --> 00:25:54,001
[Laughs]

 281 
00:26:00,512 --> 00:26:04,815
- Dr. Hasslein?
- No... nothing.

 282 
00:26:04,886 --> 00:26:07,788
- Mr. Chairman.
- Yes?

 283 
00:26:07,857 --> 00:26:12,524
- What is the male's name, please?
- Cornelius.

 284 
00:26:12,598 --> 00:26:16,366
- My lawfully wedded spouse.
- Wedded?

 285 
00:26:16,437 --> 00:26:19,100
We'll take that up later,
Your Eminence.

 286 
00:26:21,144 --> 00:26:25,105
Cornelius, do you and
your lawfully wedded spouse

 287 
00:26:25,183 --> 00:26:27,311
speak any language
other than English?

 288 
00:26:27,386 --> 00:26:29,184
What is English?

 289 
00:26:29,256 --> 00:26:31,886
I speak the language
taught to me

 290 
00:26:31,961 --> 00:26:35,524
by my father and mother,
who were taught by their
fathers and mothers before them.

 291 
00:26:35,600 --> 00:26:37,592
It has been the language
ofour ancestors

 292 
00:26:37,669 --> 00:26:39,638
for nearly 2,000 years.

 293 
00:26:39,706 --> 00:26:42,437
As to its origins,
who can be sure?

 294 
00:26:42,510 --> 00:26:46,243
Gorillas and orangutans
ofour community believe

 295 
00:26:46,315 --> 00:26:49,377
that God created the ape
in his own image.

 296 
00:26:49,454 --> 00:26:53,222
Nonsense!

 297 
00:26:53,293 --> 00:26:56,092
Cornelius, as an intellectual,
you know damned well

 298 
00:26:56,163 --> 00:26:58,861
the gorillas are a bunch
ofmilitaristic nincompoops.

 299 
00:26:58,935 --> 00:27:01,029
And the orangutans are
a bunch ofblinkered,

 300 
00:27:01,105 --> 00:27:03,506
pseudoscientific geese!

 301 
00:27:07,047 --> 00:27:09,448
As to humans, I've dissect--

 302 
00:27:09,517 --> 00:27:12,454
I've examined thousands of them.

 303 
00:27:12,522 --> 00:27:16,722
And until now, I've only discovered
2 who could talk in my life.

 304 
00:27:16,795 --> 00:27:19,629
God knows who taught them.

 305 
00:27:19,700 --> 00:27:21,635
Where we come from,

 306 
00:27:21,703 --> 00:27:24,229
apes talk.

 307 
00:27:24,307 --> 00:27:26,242
Humans are dumb.

 308 
00:27:32,185 --> 00:27:34,518
Where do you come from,
Cornelius?

 309 
00:27:35,991 --> 00:27:38,392
I'm not sure.

 310 
00:27:38,461 --> 00:27:40,362
Dr. Milo was sure.

 311 
00:27:42,067 --> 00:27:45,470
Dr. Milo was a genius
well in advance ofhis time.

 312 
00:27:45,539 --> 00:27:48,977
When the spacecraft
first landed on our seaboard,

 313 
00:27:49,044 --> 00:27:50,979
it was Dr. Milo who salvaged it.

 314 
00:27:51,047 --> 00:27:54,541
He studied it
and halfunderstood it.

 315 
00:27:54,620 --> 00:27:57,249
Half?
Was halfenough?

 316 
00:27:57,323 --> 00:28:00,522
It was enough for us to escape
when war became inevitable.

 317 
00:28:00,595 --> 00:28:03,588
Enough for Dr. Milo
to be murdered in your zoo.

 318 
00:28:03,666 --> 00:28:06,068
Enough for my wife and I
to be here now.

 319 
00:28:06,137 --> 00:28:10,405
- From where, Cornelius?
- I told you, I'm not sure.

 320 
00:28:10,477 --> 00:28:13,276
Maybe the female knows.

 321 
00:28:13,347 --> 00:28:16,147
Of course the female knows!

 322 
00:28:16,219 --> 00:28:18,347
We came from your future!

 323 
00:28:25,333 --> 00:28:28,861
That doesn't make any sense.

 324 
00:28:28,937 --> 00:28:30,872
It's the only thing that does.

 325 
00:28:30,940 --> 00:28:33,604
- Mr. Chairman.
- Yes?

 326 
00:28:33,679 --> 00:28:38,209
Cornelius, you spoke ofwar.

 327 
00:28:38,285 --> 00:28:42,451
- War between whom?
- The gorillas and whoever lives--Iived.

 328 
00:28:42,525 --> 00:28:45,428
- Will live.
- Who won the war?

 329 
00:28:45,496 --> 00:28:50,128
I don't know. Chimpanzees are pacifists.
We stayed at home.

 330 
00:28:50,203 --> 00:28:53,800
- But you left before the war had ended.
- In a spaceship.

 331 
00:28:53,875 --> 00:28:56,812
- Which Dr. Milo learned to navigate.
- Correct.

 332 
00:28:56,880 --> 00:29:00,909
Cornelius.
Did you know Colonel Taylor?

 333 
00:29:03,890 --> 00:29:06,827
No. Is he a soldier?

 334 
00:29:08,331 --> 00:29:11,267
We are peaceful creatures.

 335 
00:29:11,335 --> 00:29:13,304
We are happy to be here.

 336 
00:29:13,371 --> 00:29:15,500
May we be unchained?

 337 
00:29:30,331 --> 00:29:33,063
Here they come.
Gentlemen, do you have--

 338 
00:29:33,136 --> 00:29:35,071
No comment.
No comment.

 339 
00:29:35,139 --> 00:29:39,100
- No comment.
- No comment.

 340 
00:29:39,178 --> 00:29:41,841
- Mr. Chairman, a word.
- I'll give you one-- preposterous.

 341 
00:29:41,915 --> 00:29:45,216
- Well, can you define that,
Mr. Chairman?
- Uh, no, let me just say this.

 342 
00:29:45,287 --> 00:29:48,121
As head of this commission,
it will be our duty to sit through

 343 
00:29:48,191 --> 00:29:51,094
the facts of this bizarre affair
and pass our conclusions

 344 
00:29:51,163 --> 00:29:54,896
onto the president of the United States
for implementation.

 345 
00:29:54,968 --> 00:29:59,270
- What a load ofhogger mogger.
- Dr. Hasslein.

 346 
00:29:59,341 --> 00:30:01,606
- No comment, please.
- How will you advise the president

 347 
00:30:01,678 --> 00:30:03,613
to handle this
unique situation?

 348 
00:30:03,681 --> 00:30:05,844
- No comment.
- All right then, Dr. Hasslein,

 349 
00:30:05,919 --> 00:30:08,184
could you tell us how you
personally would handle it?

 350 
00:30:08,255 --> 00:30:12,489
No, gentlemen,
no comment...yet.

 351 
00:30:12,562 --> 00:30:14,155
Doctor.

 352 
00:30:14,231 --> 00:30:16,166
You were fabulous!

 353 
00:30:16,234 --> 00:30:18,567
You were marvelous.
They loved you. All that applause.

 354 
00:30:18,637 --> 00:30:20,833
But there was a moment--

 355 
00:30:20,907 --> 00:30:23,537
There was when he
started to ask us--

 356 
00:30:23,612 --> 00:30:25,740
Zira!

 357 
00:30:25,815 --> 00:30:29,412
-Cornelius, I think we should tell them.
-No.

 358 
00:30:29,487 --> 00:30:33,926
- But only to Lewis and Stevie.
- Oh, Zira.

 359 
00:30:33,994 --> 00:30:36,988
I have to be honest
with someone.

 360 
00:30:37,066 --> 00:30:38,898
Cornelius, please.

 361 
00:30:38,969 --> 00:30:41,438
You tell them.

 362 
00:30:44,944 --> 00:30:47,743
Well, you see...

 363 
00:30:47,815 --> 00:30:49,750
we did know Colonel Taylor.

 364 
00:30:49,818 --> 00:30:52,288
We came to love him.

 365 
00:30:52,356 --> 00:30:55,349
I don't understand what harm there could
be in telling that to the commission?

 366 
00:30:55,426 --> 00:30:59,159
Where we come from,

 367 
00:30:59,232 --> 00:31:02,533
apes did not love humans.

 368 
00:31:02,604 --> 00:31:06,042
They, uh, hunted them
for sport,

 369 
00:31:06,110 --> 00:31:08,045
much as you would animals.

 370 
00:31:08,113 --> 00:31:11,106
Yes. We use their bodies,
alive and dead,

 371 
00:31:11,183 --> 00:31:14,177
experimentally for
anatomical dissection

 372 
00:31:14,255 --> 00:31:16,918
and scientific research.

 373 
00:31:19,997 --> 00:31:24,299
Well, we do the same thing
to animals.

 374 
00:31:24,370 --> 00:31:27,069
I mean, as a scientist,
I sympathize,

 375 
00:31:27,203 --> 00:31:31,107
but I agree that that's a revelation
the masses would not take kindly to.

 376 
00:31:31,176 --> 00:31:34,636
I think you did the right thing
in denying knowledge of colonel Taylor.

 377 
00:31:34,714 --> 00:31:38,812
- There was another reason.
- Stevie: What?

 378 
00:31:38,887 --> 00:31:41,584
They would have asked
ifhe was still alive.

 379 
00:31:41,658 --> 00:31:45,187
- And is he?
- Oh, no, no, no, he can't be.

 380 
00:31:45,263 --> 00:31:47,164
Well, how did you know?

 381 
00:31:47,233 --> 00:31:49,725
Because

 382 
00:31:49,803 --> 00:31:53,833
from the windows
of the spaceship...

 383 
00:31:53,910 --> 00:31:56,903
we saw the Earth...

 384 
00:31:56,981 --> 00:31:58,916
destroyed.

 385 
00:32:05,695 --> 00:32:07,630
Stand by.

 386 
00:32:10,702 --> 00:32:13,639
Good evening, this is Bill Bonds
reporting from Los Angeles

 387 
00:32:13,707 --> 00:32:17,770
where the biggest story since
the moon landing broke this morning
when 2 apes talked.

 388 
00:32:17,846 --> 00:32:22,444
I repeat, talked to the
Presidential Commission of lnquiry .

 389 
00:32:22,519 --> 00:32:25,888
With me this evening in the studio
is Dr. Otto Hasslein.

 390 
00:32:25,958 --> 00:32:28,450
He is a senior scientific advisor
at the White House.

 391 
00:32:28,529 --> 00:32:30,725
And he'll be giving us his views
on the crucial statement

 392 
00:32:30,799 --> 00:32:32,734
made at this
morning's session.

 393 
00:32:32,802 --> 00:32:36,501
Dr. Hasslein, as I recall,
when you asked the male ape

 394 
00:32:36,575 --> 00:32:38,237
where he was from,

 395 
00:32:38,311 --> 00:32:41,804
the female replied,
"From your future."

 396 
00:32:41,882 --> 00:32:44,478
- Yes.
- Would you believe that?

 397 
00:32:44,553 --> 00:32:48,116
Absolutely. I think
it is the only explanation.

 398 
00:32:48,192 --> 00:32:50,753
Well, maybe the explanation
needs some explaining now.

 399 
00:32:50,829 --> 00:32:52,991
You've written several
learned dissertations

 400 
00:32:53,066 --> 00:32:55,126
on the nature of time.

 401 
00:32:55,202 --> 00:32:58,071
Could you explain in terms that
our viewers at home will understand?

 402 
00:32:58,141 --> 00:33:01,305
How, for instance,
a person, or persons,

 403 
00:33:01,379 --> 00:33:05,181
could travel from
time past to time future

 404 
00:33:05,252 --> 00:33:07,915
or, indeed, vice versa?

 405 
00:33:07,989 --> 00:33:10,720
Mr. Bonds, I think that time
can only be fully understood

 406 
00:33:10,793 --> 00:33:14,663
by an observer with a godlike gift
ofinfinite regression.

 407 
00:33:14,732 --> 00:33:17,669
Could you explain
infinite regression for us?

 408 
00:33:17,737 --> 00:33:19,933
- Roll the film.
- I'd more than happy to.

 409 
00:33:20,007 --> 00:33:21,942
As a matter offact,
I came prepared to do just that.

 410 
00:33:22,010 --> 00:33:24,776
Now here's a painting
of a landscape.

 411 
00:33:24,848 --> 00:33:28,911
The artist who
painted that picture

 412 
00:33:28,988 --> 00:33:30,752
says something is missing--
what is it?

 413 
00:33:30,824 --> 00:33:34,956
"It is I myself, who was part
of the landscape I painted."

 414 
00:33:35,030 --> 00:33:39,298
So he mentally takes
a step backward, or regresses,

 415 
00:33:39,370 --> 00:33:42,603
and paints a picture of the artist
painting a picture of the landscape.

 416 
00:33:42,675 --> 00:33:46,044
But still something is missing-- and
that something is still his real self

 417 
00:33:46,114 --> 00:33:48,481
painting the second picture.

 418 
00:33:48,550 --> 00:33:51,521
So he regresses further
and paints a third.

 419 
00:33:51,589 --> 00:33:54,058
A picture of the artist
painting a picture

 420 
00:33:54,126 --> 00:33:57,187
of the artist painting
a picture of the landscape.

 421 
00:33:57,263 --> 00:33:59,699
But because something
is still missing,

 422 
00:33:59,768 --> 00:34:01,703
he paints
a fourth and a fifth

 423 
00:34:01,771 --> 00:34:04,070
until he paints
a picture of the artist

 424 
00:34:04,141 --> 00:34:08,204
painting a picture of the artist
painting a picture of the artist

 425 
00:34:08,280 --> 00:34:11,445
painting a picture of the artist
painting a landscape.

 426 
00:34:11,519 --> 00:34:13,715
So infinite regression then is--

 427 
00:34:13,789 --> 00:34:17,727
It is the moment when our artist
has regressed to the point ofinfinity,

 428 
00:34:17,795 --> 00:34:19,957
and himself, becomes part
of the landscape he painted

 429 
00:34:20,031 --> 00:34:22,193
and is both the observer
and the observed.

 430 
00:34:22,268 --> 00:34:24,966
Well, now in that
peculiar condition,

 431 
00:34:25,039 --> 00:34:28,533
what would he be observing
ifhe were observing, let's say, time?

 432 
00:34:28,611 --> 00:34:32,174
He would perceive, Mr. Bonds,
that time is like a freeway

 433 
00:34:32,250 --> 00:34:34,219
with an infinite
number oflanes,

 434 
00:34:34,287 --> 00:34:36,518
all leading from
the past into the future,

 435 
00:34:36,590 --> 00:34:38,525
however, not unto the same future.

 436 
00:34:38,593 --> 00:34:42,292
A driver in lane "A" may crash
while a driver in lane "B" survives.

 437 
00:34:42,365 --> 00:34:46,235
It follows that a driver,
by changing lanes can change his future.

 438 
00:34:46,305 --> 00:34:48,934
Now, Mr. Bonds, I do not
find it diffcult to believe

 439 
00:34:49,008 --> 00:34:51,638
that in the dark and turbulent
corridors ofouter space,

 440 
00:34:51,713 --> 00:34:55,549
the impact ofsome distant planetary ,
even galactic disaster,

 441 
00:34:55,619 --> 00:34:57,815
jumped the apes from
their present into ours.

 442 
00:34:57,889 --> 00:35:00,984
Indeed, the prooflies
in their arrival among us.

 443 
00:35:01,061 --> 00:35:03,530
And in their spoken,
and I repeat spoken testimony.

 444 
00:35:03,598 --> 00:35:05,794
Thank you very much,
Dr. Hasslein.

 445 
00:35:05,868 --> 00:35:09,567
It's certainly the most incredible story
this reporter has ever covered.

 446 
00:35:09,640 --> 00:35:12,075
I think that by their intelligence
and their good humor,

 447 
00:35:12,144 --> 00:35:14,979
the 2 so-called "ape-o-nauts"
have already captured the hearts

 448 
00:35:15,048 --> 00:35:17,449
of the entire American nation.

 449 
00:35:17,519 --> 00:35:19,317
They will not be required

 450 
00:35:19,388 --> 00:35:21,323
to appear before
the commission tomorrow.

 451 
00:35:21,391 --> 00:35:23,223
That hearing, of course,
is going to be held in private.

 452 
00:35:23,294 --> 00:35:27,198
They will, however, be taken
from the zoo infirmary to a hotel,

 453 
00:35:27,267 --> 00:35:30,329
and they will be given
an extended tour of the city.

 454 
00:35:30,405 --> 00:35:33,569
This is Bill Bonds reporting
for Eyewitness News.

 455 
00:35:33,643 --> 00:35:36,307
- Good night.
- Good night.

